    <ownedClass>
        <class isAbstract="false" name="Address">
            <derivationSupplier className="Role" staticModelDerivationId="1"/>
            <graphicRepresentation presentation="HL7">
                <graphElement containerDiagramName="Main"
                    isHeightAutoSize="true" isWidthAutoSize="true"
                    shapeId="Sheet.199" shapeTemplate="Role">
                    <position x="4.26" y="6.16011"/>
                    <size height="0.51445" width="1.25"/>
                </graphElement>
            </graphicRepresentation>
            <annotations>
                <otherAnnotation type="html">
                    <text>
                        <b>This class is used to hold address details for a person. The use attribute describes the use made of the address (home, temporary, etc). The structure of this class is based on the HL7 AD data type.</b>
                    </text>
                </otherAnnotation>
            </annotations>
            <attribute conformance="R" fixedValue="LOCE"
                isMandatory="true" isStructural="true"
                maximumMultiplicity="1" minimumMultiplicity="1"
                name="classCode" sortKey="1">
                <annotations>
                    <otherAnnotation type="html">
                        <text>Indicates this is a location</text>
                    </otherAnnotation>
                </annotations>
                <derivationSupplier attributeName="classCode"
                    className="Role" staticModelDerivationId="1"/>
                <type name="CS"/>
                <supplierDomainSpecification codingStrength="CNE" domainName="LOCE"/>
            </attribute>
            <attribute conformance="R" isMandatory="true"
                maximumMultiplicity="1" minimumMultiplicity="1"
                name="addr" sortKey="5">
                <annotations>
                    <otherAnnotation type="html">
                        <text>
                            <p/>
                            <p>Address of the patient.</p>
                            <p>The particular flavour of the address datatype used here is Address streetAddressLine Typed (format 2 in the datatypes description), plus: </p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Optional Postcode</li>
                                <li>Optional Address Key</li>
                                <li>Mandatory Use</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p>This means that the address will contain the following components:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>Between one and five <i>streetAddressLine</i> elements. Excludes postcode, may be vernacular or PAF-derived. For vernacular addresses, the following formatting convention                         should be used:                          <ul>
                                    <li>Line 1: premises ID</li>
                                    <li>Line 2: no. / thoroughfare</li>
                                    <li>Line 3: locality</li>
                                    <li>Line 4: post town</li>
                                    <li>Line 5: county</li>
                                    <li>Lines 1 or 2 and line 4 are mandatory</li>
                                    </ul>
                                </li>
                                <li>A <i>postalCode</i> element to carry a postcode (<i>optional</i>)                       </li>
                                <ul>
                                    <li>This UK format Postcode, 8 character string, e.g. ZZ99 3VZ (as per BS7666 standard). <br/>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>The 8 characters field allows a space to be inserted to differentiate between the inward and outward segments of the code,                            enabling full use to be made of Royal Mail postcode functionality.                          </li>
                                </ul>
                                <li>An <i>addressKey</i> element to carry a PAF key (Postcode Address File). PAF is a data file available from the Royal Mail(<i>optional</i>)                      </li>
                                <li>The <i>use</i> attribute to denote the type of address (<i>mandatory</i>).                       </li>
                            </ul>
                            <p/>
                            <p/>
                            <p/>
                            <p>5 address lines - excludes postcode, may be vernacular or PAF-derived. For vernacular addresses, the following formatting                   convention should normally apply although there may be some exceptions:  <br/>
                            </p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>line 1: premises ID</li>
                                <li>line 2: no/thoroughfare</li>
                                <li>line 3: locality</li>
                                <li>line 4: post town</li>
                                <li>line 5: county</li>
                            </ul>The following address lines should normally be mandatory although there may be some exceptions:<br/>
                            <ul>
                                <li>1 or 2 and</li>
                                <li>4</li>
                            </ul>
                            <p>The  usable period attribute is used to hold the dates for which this data is/was current as a range, supplied in the Low                      and High attributes of the IVL_TS. Business Effective Dates are full dates without time                   </p>
                            <bp/>
                        </text>
                    </otherAnnotation>
                </annotations>
                <derivationSupplier attributeName="addr"
                    className="Role" staticModelDerivationId="1"/>
                <type name="AD"/>
            </attribute>
        </class>
    </ownedClass>
